-- 
CANADA DAYBOOK: Bank of Canada Makes Rates Announcement

-- B y   D a v i d   S c a n l a n
-- 
2011-05-31T05:01:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/canada-daybook-bank-of-canada-makes-rates-announcement.html
The  Bank of Canada  makes its interest
rate announcement in Ottawa, while Bank of Nova Scotia releases
second-quarter earnings.  ECONOMY:
*The Bank of  Canada  makes an interest rate announcement at 9
a.m. New York time, with all 24 economists surveyed by Bloomberg
forecasting the key policy rate will remain at 1 percent.
*Statistics Canada reports on factory inflation data for April
at 8:30 a.m. in Ottawa. The industrial product price index is
forecast to have risen 0.7 percent on the month and the raw
materials price index is forecast to have increased 3 percent,
according to Bloomberg News surveys.
*Finance Minister Jim Flaherty meets private-sector economists
in Toronto to shape forecasts for his June 6 budget, and speaks
to reporters at noon.  EVENTS:
* Bank of Nova Scotia (BNS) , Canada’s third-largest bank, is scheduled
to release second-quarter results at about 7:30 a.m. The
Toronto-based lender is expected to earn profit before one-time
items of C$1.09 a share, according to the average estimate of 15
analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News.
*Pacific Rubiales Energy Corp., an oil producer with operations
in  Colombia , is to hold its annual meeting at 10 a.m. in
Toronto.
*Oilfield-services provider Trinidad Drilling Ltd. is to report
first-quarter earnings after markets close. Analysts forecast
the company earned 19 cents a share, excluding certain
items, according the average of 10 estimates in a Bloomberg
survey.
*Industry Minister Christian Paradis speaks at a
telecommunications conference in Toronto at 2 p.m. about the
government’s plans for the industry.  MARKETS:
*The S&P/TSX climbed 32.07 points to 13,829.66.
*Yields on two-year Government of Canada bonds fell one basis
point to 1.50 percent.
*The Canadian dollar fell 0.1 percent to 97.71 cents per  U.S.
dollar .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Scanlan at   dscanlan@Bloomberg.net  